Published on October 13, 2023 6:32 PM GMT<br/><br/><p>This is a accompanying blog post to work done by Callum McDougall, Arthur Conmy and Cody Rushing as part of SERI MATS 2023. The work was mentored by Neel Nanda and Tom McGrath. You can find our full paper at <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.04625." rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.04625.</a> We i) summarize our key results, ii) discuss limitations and future work and iii) list lessons learnt from the project</p><h1>Key Results</h1><h2>Copy Suppression</h2><p>In the paper, we define <strong>copy suppression</strong> as the following algorithm:</p><blockquote><p>If components in earlier layers predict a certain token, and this token appears earlier in the context, the attention head suppresses it.</p></blockquote><p>We show that attention head L10H7 in GPT2-Small (and to a lesser extent L11H10) both perform copy suppression <strong>across the whole distribution, and this algorithm explains 76.9% of their behavior</strong>. </p><p>For example, take the sentence &#34;All&#39;s fair in love and war.&#34; If we ablate L10H7, the model will incorrectly predict &#34;...love and love.&#34; A diagram of this process:</p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Os8ZqRJST_aQlCC2N7XR4OGuHCjCVXBxmTsQG2GbHec=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy9lYmV6c0hXNnFKd3hURmFzWC9vc3M5MDZ2cW1mc21wazhndWdjZg==" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/MRCMJ56905Dnsc3CIbH4BqfG3feY42oY1-q2xjKceuU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy9lYmV6c0hXNnFKd3hURmFzWC9pdHR6dnlobmVveGhxZ214dWR4NA== 140w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/aMcQ0_6S9hNQICqmV0AUK1lP2JH9uwvKE7b6uWFHqeI=/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXMuY2xvdWRpbmFyeS5jb20vbGVzc3dyb25nLTItMC9pbWFnZS91cGxvYWQvZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0by92MS9taXJyb3JlZEltYWdlcy9lYmV6c0hXNnFKd3hURmFzWC9laX